narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I would definitely recommend this class if it is ever offered again.
I would absolutely recommend it. You'll learn things that not every American should understand.
It's a class that overviews theories of empire and its unravelling in the 20th century.
Yes, if the subject is interesting to you.

An intellectual journey through the late 19th-mid 20th century. Basically reading a bunch of primary and some secondary sources about colonization/decolonization. I couldn't actually tell you a timeline of these events because it was a lot more existential and theoretical, "what is empire" "is_____ just a new version of the imperial system" etc. Irwin is leaving Yale so I don't know if this class will be taught again but if so, take if you like reading political theory, don't take if you like knowing hard facts.

Decolonization is a great class. Ryan Irwin is really great to work with. Leads great discussions and has wonderful feedback. If you're a European or American centered history person and looking for a really interesting rest of the world course, this is it.
A great class, one of the best things is the way it looked at world events today or in the recent past through the lens of decolonization in the 20th century.
